post_text:
Favor de completer esta forma del departamento de Child Nutrition Services para ayudarnos a planificar adecuadamente el programa.

https://forms.gle/Gkt4NWGPRziCvzHz5

El Departamento de Nutrición, del Distrito Escolar de Oxnard, está desarrollando un Plan de Distribución de Alimentos para satisfacer las necesidades de nuestros estudiantes al empezar el aprendizaje a distancia. Al comienzo de la instrucción a distancia, el Distrito Escolar de Oxnard proporcionará alimentos para llevar a casa para los estudiantes matriculados. Favor de completer este formulario para ayudarnos a planificar adecuadamente el programa.

El Distrito Escolar de Oxnard continúa participando en el Programa de Eligibilidad de la Comunidad, que permite que todos los alumnos matriculados en nuestras escuelas reciban comida sin ningún cobro. Esperamos que te unas a nosotros en nuestros dias de distribución de alimentos en en los locales: Marshall, Fremont, Frank, Ramona, Lemonwood, Harrington, McKinna y Driffill.

post_text:
Please fill this form out to assist Child Nutrition Services in properly planning for Meal distribution:

https://forms.gle/Gkt4NWGPRziCvzHz5

Oxnard School District Child Nutrition Department is in the process of developing a Meal Distribution Plan to meet the needs of our students when distance learning begins. When instruction begins, Oxnard School District will provide take home meals for enrolled students.

OSD continues to participate in the Community Eligibility Program, which allows all students enrolled in our schools to receive meals at no charge. We look forward to having you join us on our Meal Distribution days located at: Marshall, Fremont, Frank, Ramona, Lemonwood, Harrington, McKinna and Driffill.

Hello Oxnard Families

The Oxnard School District's 1 to 1 device program has a limited inventory of Wi-Fi hot spots available to check out to students for academic use. 𝑻𝒉𝒆 𝒉𝒐𝒕 𝒔𝒑𝒐𝒕𝒔 𝒄𝒂𝒏 𝒐𝒏𝒍𝒚 𝒄𝒐𝒏𝒏𝒆𝒄𝒕 𝒕𝒐 𝑶𝑺𝑫 𝒊𝑷𝒂𝒅𝒔 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒉𝒂𝒗𝒆 𝒇𝒊𝒍𝒕𝒆𝒓𝒆𝒅 𝒊𝒏𝒕𝒆𝒓𝒏𝒆𝒕 (𝑵𝒐 𝑯𝒖𝒍𝒖, 𝑵𝒆𝒕𝒇𝒍𝒊𝒙, 𝒍𝒊𝒎𝒊𝒕𝒆𝒅 𝒀𝒐𝒖𝑻𝒖𝒃𝒆 𝒂𝒄𝒄𝒆𝒔𝒔, 𝒆𝒕𝒄.)

Each family is limited to one device per household. Completion of this application does not guarantee your household will receive a Wi-Fi hot spot device. In the event the district receives more applications than available Wi-Fi hot spots, the devices will be allocated based on Socio-Economic need, Foster Youth or Special Program enrollment. An application must be completed each academic school year for consideration.

Wi-Fi Hotspot applications are now available at your school’s front office or via web:

https://tinyurl.com/OSDwifiapp

post_text: Starting tomorrow! On Monday, June 22, the Summer Feeding Program will distribute weekly meal boxes (see example below) on Mondays ONLY to families in the community with children ages 1-18 years old at the following NEW school site locations starting at 8:30 am: Lemonwood School, Driffill School, RJ Frank Middle School, and Fremont Middle School. It is recommended that you bring a cart, stroller, wagon, or someone to help carry the boxed meals if possible. Supplies are limited. First come, first served.

post_text:
Today is School Lunch Hero Day! Now, more than ever, the Child Nutrition Services (CNS) Department at the Oxnard School District is making a difference in our community. Each week CNS serves 4,000 meal bags in our community with each bag containing five breakfast meals and five lunch meals. CNS is employing approximately 340 hours weekly of labor to prepare theses meals. To date, CNS has served a phenomenal 88,486 free meals to children 1-18 years old in our community since the start of shelter-in-place order.

Suzanne Lugotoff, CNS Director said: "Thank you CNS team for your dedication, your service, and your warm smiles that show you care!"
text:
Today is School Lunch Hero Day! Now, more than ever, the Child Nutrition Services (CNS) Department at the Oxnard School District is making a difference in our community. Each week CNS serves 4,000 meal bags in our community with each bag containing five breakfast meals and five lunch meals. CNS is employing approximately 340 hours weekly of labor to prepare theses meals. To date, CNS has served a phenomenal 88,486 free meals to children 1-18 years old in our community since the start of shelter-in-place order.

Suzanne Lugotoff, CNS Director said: "Thank you CNS team for your dedication, your service, and your warm smiles that show you care!"

post_text: Oxnard School District Trustees will fill a vacancy on the Board through a provisional appointment for the Trustee Area 2 seat. Interested individuals who are at least 18 years old, a registered voter, and reside in Trustee Area 2 may download an application at www.oxnardsd.org or pick up an application at the Oxnard School District Office, 1051 South A Street, in Oxnard. Completed applications must be received at the District Office no later than 5 p.m. on Friday, May 15, 2020. Current members of the Board of Trustees will interview and appoint a Trustee for Area 2 applicants in open session at a special meeting on Wednesday, May 27 at 5 p.m. To access the Notice of Vacancy, Timeline, Application, and Trustee Area Map, go to www.oxnardsd.org. For questions, please call (805) 385-1501, ext. 2034 or email Lydia Garcia at lgarcia@oxnardsd.org.

post_text: Meal distribution to feed children in the community ages 1-18 years old happening today from 9 a.m. to noon at Driffill, Harrington, Cesar Chavez, and Fremont schools. The weekly meals includes five days worth of breakfast and lunch staple foods. Staple items are based on availability. Supplies are limited and all meals will be distributed on a first-come, first-served basis. If you struggle to get to one of these OSD locations, please note that additional school districts are also offering meals at no cost. Hueneme, Oxnard Union High School District, Ventura Unified, and Rio are all offering meals to community members. For a list of locations, visit www.vcoe.org/meals.

post_text: Foodshare will be providing meals to the Oxnard community on Wednesday, April 15 from 3:00 p.m. until the food is gone. The location is at Oxnard College Park, 3250 South Rose Avenue (parking lot next to baseball fields). Distributions are limited to low-income families residing in the city of that distribution. An ID or proof of residence is required upon arrival. ALL distribution sites are drive-thru only for the safety of you and our staff. Food is limited to ONE box per household on a first come, first served basis. post_text: There will be a Special Board Meeting on Friday, March 27 starting at 2 p.m. The Oxnard School District is committed to public input and participation in school district governance in a manner that is consistent with guidance provided by Ventura County Public Health officials. Given the current shelter in place order in Ventura County, we are requiring remote, online participation in order to promote the safety and health of our community. In-person public participation will not be allowed during this period due to the health and safety risks it poses. You can call into the meeting to provide public comment via Zoom. You can join the Zoom Meeting from a computer, mobile device, or tablet. The Zoom meeting information will be provided on the district’s website for every board meeting agenda, as long as needed during the COVID-19 pandemic. For more information, please click on this link: https://www.oxnardsd.org/Page/11118. Thank you.

post_text: Kamala School Assistant Principal Brian Blevins agreed to have pies in the face to celebrate the school exceeding its $500 fundraising goal to benefit The Leukemia & Lymphoma Society. The nonprofit organization's "Pennies for Patients" ensures that no child has to take on cancer alone. Students and staff at Kamala School ended up exceeding the goal by raising a total of $1,958! As a science-based service-learning program, "Pennies for Patients" connects schools with local blood cancer patients, provides tangible life skills to participants, and allows students to see the impact they’re making in the lives of others. Way to go!

post_text: Students in 6th - 8th grades at Richard B. Haydock Intermediate School's "Earth Club" as well as AVID students visited Oxnard College as part of a service learning project to learn more about the college. The project (in partnership with U.S.Fish and Wildlife Service, Oxnard College maintenance Bob Sube, Oxnard College professors Michael Nicholson and Jim Danza, and Oxnard College students) included a tour of the school campus and the planting of native plants along Bard Road. Over 250 native plants have been planted as a result of efforts by students from both Haydock and Curren School’s "Earth Keepers" Club back in December. This partnership is planned for a third round of plantings during the next school year.

post_text:
Dear OSD Family,
As you know, there was a shooting incident that occurred this morning off campus near McAuliffe School. As a result, one student was injured and suffered non-life threatening injuries. The school was immediately placed on lockdown and the Oxnard Police Department responded immediately. Today’s events unfolded rather quickly and our first priority was ensuring the safety and security of all students and staff. We will have additional school counselors and psychologists available at school tomorrow for students and staff as well as an increase in police presence. I would like to thank the principal, teachers, and McAuliffe team for taking care of the students in a caring and loving manner. We also thank the Oxnard Police Department for their immediate response to this incident. Lastly, I would like to thank McAuliffe parents and families for their understanding and patience today during this stressful incident. We will continue to ensure the safety and securing of our students and staff. Thank you.
Dr. Karling Aguilera-Fort
Superintendent
Oxnard School District

post_text: There is still time to get tickets to attend the OSD Education Foundation Gala happening on Saturday, February 8 from 6 p.m.-10 p.m.at the Saticoy Country Club. Tickets are $90/person and includes music by Jeanne Tatum, hors d’oeuvres, gourmet dinner & beverage, a silent & live auction, and dancing. This annual gala is the primary fundraiser for the Oxnard Education Foundation which utilizes the funds raised to offer the "Awards of Excellence" to recognize over 1,500 students annually. The foundation also awards grants in the amount of about $15,000 per year for teachers and staff. The deadline to purchase tickets is January 31, 2020. Contact Sue Odgers at (805) 390-9895 or email odgersfam@roadrunner.com.

post_text:
Statement regarding today's (1-16-2020) incident at Haydock Academy of Arts & Sciences:

Late this afternoon, Haydock Middle School was placed on a lockdown due to an intruder on campus. All students and staff that were on campus for the after-school program and other after-school activities are safe. At approximately 4:20 pm, some students noticed an unknown individual walk on campus with a weapon. Because that person posed a threat, administrators at the school immediately initiated lockdown procedures and alerted the Oxnard Police Department. Law enforcement quickly responded and conducted a full sweep of the entire campus. The individual was not found. As always, the safety of our students and staff is our first priority and we followed all safety policies and procedures.

post_text: Did you know? Research shows that missing only 10 percent of school, or about 18 days in most school districts, negatively affects a student’s academic performance. That’s just two days a month and is considered chronic absenteeism. This plays a critical role in student achievement. By working together, all of us can ensure all children can get to school every day so they have an opportunity to learn, flourish and realize their dreams.#AttendanceMatters

post_text: Students from Curren School's "Earth Keepers Club" and Ms. Moser’s 3rd grade class created native plant habitats at Oxnard College. This hands-on, learning opportunity happened in partnership with the college's Director of Facilities, Bob Sube, and Oxnard College science professors, Michael Nicholson and Jim Danza, along with Michael Glenn from U.S.Fish and Wildlife Service. Students were also given a tour of the campus to learn more about college.

post_text: Spreading holiday cheer! The Oxnard Police Department 9th annual "Heroes & Helpers" program welcomed thirty well-deserving students from Oxnard School District schools who were chosen to shop at Target Store Oxnard-West with local first responders and Target team members. OSD students were selected by the School Resource Officers in partnership with the school principals and counselors. Students were treated to a "meet and greet" with Mr. and Mrs. Santa Claus before participating in a $200 shopping spree. The "Heroes & Helpers" program fosters strong community relationships by pairing public safety officials with youth to shop for the children’s families during the holiday season. Thank you to all who supported this effort!
